We recommended for the Management to:
Create an Inspectorate Committee with adequate number of members to be able to complete the physical inventory in three months or less, who will coordinate with the City General Services Office (CGSO) in the preparation of a Physical Inventory Plan (PIP), in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, to promote the conduct of the required annual physical count of PPE in compliance with COA Circular              No. 2002-003 dated June 20, 2002 and to address the unreconciled balances between the Accounting Office and CGSO caused by   non-existing/missing PPEs without available record of accountability;
Require the CGSO to coordinate with the Accounting Office to determine the items to be included in the RPCPPE with consideration on the capitalization threshold of ₱15,000.00 and with the Inspectorate Committee on the details and other relevant information to ensure the proper accomplishment of the RPCPPE based on the guidelines provided under COA Circular                Nos. 2002-003 dated June 20, 2002 and 2020-006 dated         January 31, 2020;
Require the Accounting Office to maintain the required Property Plant and Equipment Ledger Card (PPELC) or its equivalent to record all acquisitions, depreciations, disposals and other information about the PPE to facilitate the reconciliation of any noted discrepancy between the records of the Accounting and the General Services Offices;
Facilitate the application of a one-time cleansing of PPE accounts in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated           January 31, 2020; and
Consider increasing the number of personnel in the Accounting Office to address the manpower constraints in the said Office and facilitate the maintenance of the required records.

4.11	We recommended that Management:
Require the City Accountant to immediately establish and maintain separate subsidiary ledgers for the following: (a) unexpended balances of LDRRMF by year of transfer; (b) receipts of NDRRMF by transferring agency; (c) DRRMF from other LGUs by LGU; and (d) other sources by donor;
Include in the LDRRMF Investment plan under a separate caption the PPAs charged to the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years; review and update the plan annually to increase the disaster-resilience capability of the City;
Require the CDRRM Officer, the City Accountant and the Budget Officer to coordinate and reconcile the prior years’ unexpended/unobligated balances of LDRRMF; and
Submit to the Office of the Auditor, the breakdown of PPAs for the ₱53,000,000.00 reprogrammed amount from the CDRRM Trust Fund.

We recommended that Management direct the BAC to strictly comply with the provisions of the Revised IRR of RA 9184, specifically on the following:

Invite the COA and observer from duly recognized private group not only during pre-bid and bid opening but also during the eligibility checking, short listing and post-qualification of bidders;

Ensure that the notice of pre-procurement, pre-bid, bid-opening and post-qualification conferences of BAC are duly received by the representative of the private group and NGO, and attach copy of the duly received notice to the contract;   

Post within three (3) days and 15 days the NOA and NTP, respectively, and copy of the approved contracts in the PhilGEPS and the City websites and the NOA in any conspicuous place in the premises of the City;

Issue certification on the posting of the NOA and NTP and copy of the approved contracts to the PhilGEPS website, the City website and the NOA in any conspicuous place in the premises of the City; and

Attach to the contracts submitted for review and to the corresponding disbursement vouchers, the print-outs on the result of the posting of the NOA, NTP and copy of the approved contract in the PhilGEPS and City websites, and the certification   issued by the BAC Secretariat for the posting in any conspicuous place in the premises of the City.

We recommended that Management:

Set aside political conflicts, coordinate and unite for efficient implementation of development programs, projects and activities;

Direct the Local Development Committee, thru the CPDO, to give priority in the preparation of necessary documents on the projects that need to be implemented during the year;

Properly screen the project proposals submitted by the barangays and prioritize the development projects that are readily implementable and with complete documents; and

Instruct the BAC to observe procurement timelines prescribed in the 2016 Revised IRR of RA 9184 and that in the preparation of the Annual Procurement Plan/PPMP, the projects listed in the 20% Development Plan should be given utmost priority on their procurement activities.

We recommended that Management:

	a. Endevor the implementation of disaster mitigation, preparedness and response capability programs and projects to effectively prevent the onslaught on lives and properties of the people of Cabadbaran City in times of natural disaster;

	b. Implement the City Government’s programs/projects/activities relating to disaster risk reduction in accordance with its LDRRMF Investment Plan;

	Maximize available resources on the local DRRMF for disaster mitigation and preparedness in order to build the resilience of the City against disasters including climate change impacts; and


	Proper review of the budget by the City Budget Officer to ensure the inclusion of all sources of LDRRMF in the General Fund Annual Budget pursuant to Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-1 dated March 25, 2013 issued by NDRRMC, DBM and DILG.

